AVIAN INFLUENZA, HUMAN - TURKEY (04): SUSPECTED
***********************************************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.promedmail.org>
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
<http://www.isid.org>
[1]
Date: Thu 5 Jan 2006
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: The Guardian newspaper, Thu 5 Jan 2006 [edited]
<http://www.guardian.co.uk/print/0,3858,5367303-112338,00.html>

A boy is believed to have died from avian influenza in Turkey, its
government said last night, while his sister was seriously ill with the
same virus. They are the 1st human cases outside southeast Asia, bringing
the spectre of the feared pandemic to the European border.
The boy, aged 14, died on Sunday [1 Jan 2006] amid initial assertions from
the Turkish authorities that he did not have the H5N1 virus which causes
avian flu. His sister was said at the time to be in a critical condition.
But the Turkish health minister, Recep Akdag, said yesterday that
preliminary tests had [detected] the H5N1 avian influenza virus. A 3rd
sibling is also suspected of having the virus.
The British government will be closely monitoring developments in Turkey
after the news, a spokesman for the Department of Environment, Food and
Rural Affairs said last night."The cases in Asia have been among people who
have been closely involved with sick birds. Close contact is needed to
transmit this from bird to human," he said. Poultry workers are urged to
minimise risks by maintaining good hygiene, washing hands, isolating any
birds that may be sick and alerting the authorities.
The Turkish Health Minister said the authorities had repeated the test in 2
separate laboratories after an autopsy on the boy. "There are 2 cases that
have been confirmed as positive by the laboratory," he said. "Another case
is suspected of being positive." As in China and Viet Nam, the boy who died
and his siblings had close contact with chickens. Their family raised them
and they handled them on a regular basis. The children's father told the
Anatolia news agency that the whole family had eaten sick birds, but that
only the children became ill. 2 days later, they developed nausea and a
high fever.
The boy, his brother, and 2 sisters were admitted to hospital in the
southeastern province of Van on Saturday [21 Dec 2005]. Huseyin Avni Sahin,
chief physician at the hospital, said a total of 11 people, including
members of the [boy's] family, were either being treated or under
observation for suspected avian influenza.
News of the cases will cause concern across Europe. Although there is no
evidence that the virus is being transmitted from one human to another,
which is the necessary precursor to a human flu pandemic, the more often
humans become infected with the H5N1 avian flu virus, the greater the
chances that it will find an opportunity to [evolve] into a form which has
that ability.
"This is disturbing information, but we expect to see sporadic cases of
bird flu in humans in an environment where there is significant bird flu
among poultry," Dr David Nabarro, coordinator for avian influenza at the
UN, said. "This is not the start of the pandemic. The pandemic starts when
there is human-to-human transfer, confirmed and sustained."
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
