[3]
Date: Thu 5 Jan 2006
From: Mary Marshall <tropical.forestry@btinternet.com>
Source: Reuters Foundation AlertNet, Thu 5 Jam 2006 [edited]
<http://www.alertnet.org/thenews/newsdesk/L05314061.htm>

6 people have been sent to hospital in a 2nd province in eastern Turkey
with suspected avian influenza, NTV commercial television reported on
Thursday [5 Jan 2006].
The news follows the death of 2 teenagers, a brother and sister, in Van
hospital in eastern Turkey overnight in the 1st [suspected] human cases of
bird flu outside China and Southeast Asia.
NTV said the 6 patients were from Igdir province on the Armenian border,
just to the north of Agri province where the 2 dead children came from. 7
other people from Agri are also being treated in Van hospital for suspected
avian influenza.
--
Mary Marshall
<tropical.forestry@btinternet.com>
[Until the results of the independent tests in progress in the UK become
available, all these cases should be regarded as suspected human cases
only. Despite the reassuring statements from WHO sources and others, if
these cases are confirmed as human cases of H5N1 avian influenza virus
infection, the situation in Turkey is qualitatively different from that in
East Asia in terms of the number of people that may be involved. In East
Asia human cases have been sporadic and usually have affected single
individuals only. The situation in Turkey remains unclear. - Mod.CP]
